Boscarian,

Welcome to what may well be the biggest money sink in all of EQ.  First of all, while you can begin alchemy at lvl 25 you probably should wait until at least 29.  The reason for this is you can only raise alchemy skill to 5 at lvl 25 and 5/level after that.  Drop 20 trains into it at 29 and skillup the remainder doing potions.  What potions?  Personally I started making SoW potions since that's why I started alchemy in the first place.  Failure rate is high but at least you have something your alts can use (my cleric was VERY happy) or sell for a decent profit.

It will cost you approx (depending on faction and cha) 105pp for enough herbs to attempt 20 combines on SoW potions.  There are cheaper potions to make and skillup on but they don't sell well, so skilling up on SoW at least gives some return.  Once SoW goes trivial try IVU or shrink.  I've had limited success selling those to players.  I emphasize the selling to players bit because this represents the most economical path to skilling up.  If you are a high level shaman and not worried about plat dump the 20 training points and then just start pumping potions.  First SoW until it is trivial, then pick another off the list... and so on.

For a very complete guide to potions, costs, etc. go to <A HREF="HTTP://www.eqtraders.com" TARGET="_BLANK">www.eqtraders.com</A> and check out their alchemy pages.  

